obj_root_law_sections_37_content:
  string
  line 37
  line `section 24 1 [or an order passed by the Director-General or Director under section 17A] may appeal to the`
  line `Appellate Tribunal within sixty days of the date on which the order is communicated to him.]`
  line `( 2 ) An appeal to the Appellate Tribunal under sub-section ( 1 ) shall be in the prescribed form and shall`
  line `be verified in the prescribed manner and shall be accompanied by a fee of 2 [two hundred rupees].`
  line `( 3 ) The provisions of 3 [sub-sections ( 3 ), ( 5 ), ( 9 ) and ( 10 )] of section 23 shall apply in relation to any`
  line `appeal under this section as they apply in relation to any appeal under that section.`
  line `26. Reference to High Court. — 4 [( 1 ) The assessee or the 5 [Chief Commissioner or Commissioner]`
  line `may, within sixty days of the date upon which he is served with notice of an order under section 23 or`
  line `section 6 [or clause ( e ) of sub-section ( 1 ) of section 34] by application in the prescribed form`
  line `accompanied, where the application is made by the assessee, by a fee of 7 [two hundred rupees], require`
  line `the Appellate Tribunal to refer to the High Court any question of law arising out of such order and,`
  line `subject to the other provisions contained in this section, the Appellate Tribunal shall, within one hundred`
  line `and twenty days of the receipt of such application, draw up a statement of the case and refer it to the High`
  line Court.
  line `( 2 ) The Appellate Tribunal may, if it is satisfied that the applicant was prevented by sufficient cause`
  line `from presenting the application within the period specified in sub-section ( 1 ), allow it to be presented`
  line `within a further period not exceeding thirty days.]`
  line `( 3 ) If, on an application made under sub-section ( 1 ), the Appellate Tribunal, —`
  line `( a ) refuses to state a case on the ground that no question of law arises, or`
  line `( b ) rejects it on the ground that it is time barred,`
  line `the applicant may, within ninety days from the date on which he is served with a notice of refusal or`
  line `rejection, as the case may be, apply to the High Court, and the High Court may, if it is not satisfied with`
  line `the correctness of the decision of the Appellate Tribunal, require the Appellate Tribunal to state the case`
  line `to the High Court, and on receipt of such requisition the Appellate Tribunal shall state the case:`
  line `Provided that, if in any case where the Appellate Tribunal has been required by an assessee to state a`
  line `case, the Appellate Tribunal refuses to do so on the ground that no question of law arises, the assessee`
  line `may, within thirty days from the date on which he receives notice of refusal to state the case, withdraw his`
  line `application, and if he does so, the fee paid by him under sub-section ( 1 ) shall be refunded to him.`
  line `8 [( 3A ) If, on an application made under this section, the Appellate Tribunal is of the opinion that on`
  line `account of a conflict in the decisions of High Courts in respect of any particular question of law, it is`
  line `expedient that a reference should be made direct to the Supreme Court, the Appellate Tribunal may draw`
  line `up a statement of the case and refer it through its President direct to the Supreme Court.]`
  line `( 4 ) The statement to the High Court 8 [or the Supreme Court] shall set forth the facts, the`
  line `determination of the Appellate Tribunal, and the question of law which arises out of the case.`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 3 of 1989, s. 89 (w.e.f. 1-4-1989).`
  line `2. Subs. by Act 16 of 1981, s. 33, for “one hundred and twenty - five rupees” (w.e.f. 1 -6-1981).`
  line `3. Subs. by Act 45 of 1972, s. 23 for “sub -sections ( 3 ) and ( 5 ) to ( 10 ) inclusive” (w.e.f. 1 -1-1973).`
  line `4. Subs. by Act 53 of 1962, s. 21, for “sub -section ( 1 ) and ( 2 ) (w.e.f. 1-4-1963).`
  line `5. Subs. by Act 4 of 1988, s. 161, for “Commissioner” (w.e.f. 1 -4-1988).`
  line `6. Ins. by Act 49 of 1991, s. 88 (w.e.f. 27-9-1991).`
  line `7. Subs. by Act 16 of 1981, s. 34, for “one hundred and twenty - five rupees” (w.e.f. 1 -6-1981).`
  line `8. Ins. by Act 53 of 1962, s. 21, (w.e.f. 1-4-1963).`
