obj_root_law_sections_38_content:
  string
  line 38
  line `( 5 ) If the High Court 1 [or the Supreme Court] is not satisfied that the case as stated is sufficient to`
  line `enable it to determine the question of law raised thereby, it may require the Appellate Tribunal to make`
  line `such modification therein as it may direct.`
  line `(6) The High Court 1 [or the Supreme Court], upon hearing any such case, shall decide the question of`
  line `law raised therein, and in doing so, may, if it thinks fit, alter the form of the question of law and shall`
  line `deliver judgment thereon containing the grounds on which such decision is founded and shall send a copy`
  line `of the judgment under the seal of the court and the signature of the Registrar to the Appellate Tribunal`
  line `and the Appellate Tribunal shall pass such orders as are necessary to dispose of the case conformably to`
  line `such judgment.`
  line `2 [( 7 ) The costs of any reference to the High Court or the Supreme Court which shall not include the`
  line `fee for making the reference shall be in the discretion of the court.]`
  line `27. Hearing by High Court. — When a case has been stated to the High Court under section 26, it`
  line `shall be heard by a Bench of not less than two Judges of the High Court and shall be decided in`
  line `accordance with the opinion of such Judges or of the majority of such Judges, if any:`
  line `Provided that where there is no such majority, the Judges shall state the point of law upon which they`
  line `differ and the case shall then be heard upon that point only by one or more of the Judges of the High`
  line `Court, and such point shall be decided according to the opinion of the majority of the Judges who have`
  line `heard the case, including those who first heard it.`
  line `28. Appeal to Supreme Court. — ( 1 ) An appeal shall lie to the Supreme Court from any judgment`
  line `of the High Court delivered on a case stated under section 26 in any case which the High Court certifies`
  line `as a fit case for appeal to the Supreme Court.`
  line `( 2 ) Where the judgment of the High Court is varied or reversed on appeal under this section, effect`
  line `shall be given to the order of the Supreme Court in the manner provided in sub-section ( 6 ) of section 26.`
  line `( 3 ) The High Court may, on application made to it for the execution of any order of the Supreme`
  line `Court in respect of any costs awarded by it, transmit the order for execution to any court subordinate to`
  line `the High Court.`
  line `3 [28A. Tax to be paid notwithstanding reference, etc. — Notwithstanding that a reference has`
  line `been made to the High Court or the Supreme Court, or an appeal has been preferred to the Supreme`
  line `Court, tax shall be payable in accordance with the assessment made in the case.`
  line `28B. Definition of High Court. — In this Chapter, “High Court” means —`
  line `( i ) in relation to any State, the High Court of that State;`
  line `4 [( ii ) in relation to the Union territory of Delhi, the High Court of Delhi;`
  line `5 * * * * *]`
  line `6 [( iii ) in relation to the Union territories of Arunachal Pradesh and Mizoram, the Gauhati High`
  line `Court (the High Court of Assam, Nagaland, Meghalaya, Manipur and Tripura);]`
  line `1. Ins. by Act 53 of 1962, s. 21 (w.e.f. 1-4-1963).`
  line `2. Subs. by s. 21, ibid., for sub-section ( 7 ), ( 8 ) and ( 9 ) (w.e.f. 1-4-1963).`
  line `3. Ins. by s. 22, ibid, (w.e.f. 1-4-1963).`
  line `4. Subs. by the Punjab Reorganisation and Delhi High Court (Adaptation of Laws on Union Subjects) Order, 1968, for clause ( ii )`
  line `(w.r.e.f. 1-11-1966).`
  line `5. Clause ( iia ) omitted by State of Himachal Pradesh (Adaptation of Laws on Union Subjects) Order, 1973 (w.r.e.f. 25-1-1971).`
  line `6. Subs. by the North-Eastern Areas (Reorganisation) (Adaptation of Laws on Union Subjects) Order, 1974, for clause ( iii )`
  line `(w.r.e.f. 21-1-1972.)`
